The article discusses a speech given by U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, Dr. Benjamin Carson, to a group of interns. Secretary Carson focused on empowering underprivileged populations in the United States and shared his own story of overcoming poverty to become a renowned neurosurgeon. The discussion touched on various factors contributing to American poverty, such as generational poverty, incarceration, racial disparities, and housing conditions. Secretary Carson highlighted initiatives aimed at addressing these issues, such as public-private partnerships and repurposing vacant buildings. The speech inspired the author to continue working as a servant leader, particularly in helping inner-city communities. The author expressed confidence in the current administration's commitment to reviving communities and ensuring the American Dream for all.